		<a name="49388"></a>
		<img src="icon_posticon.gif" border="0" hspace="3"><font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;07/15/2002&nbsp;:&nbsp; 10:09:20</font>

		&nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&amp;id=469"><img src="icon_profile.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Show Profile" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>
        
			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=469')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&amp;REPLY_ID=49388&amp;TOPIC_ID=6036&amp;FORUM_ID=2&amp;CAT_ID=1&amp;Forum_Title=General+Discussions&amp;Topic_Title=EQ+stock+market&amp;M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         I think what she is asking about is the buy low and sell high market. You can make some good cash doing this. I will caution that it appears that it is harder to do these days then it was in days past. Just seems harder all around to sell items these days.</P><P>Anyway, the theory is pretty simple. Watch your auction channel for a while to get a feel as to what items are in demand, and what their appoximate prices are. Most importantly, get to know the range of prices an item is worth. </P><P>Then, watch for items that are being sold at the lower end of the spectrum, and snap them up (after haggling a bit of course). Then auction to sell them at the higher end.</P><P>Some good items that always seem to sell under 10K might be FBSS, Sash of the DB, SCHW, Eboots, Obulus Death Shroud, Lammy, Jade Mace, Grey Flesh Sleeves, ect. Some of the bigger ticket items that move well might be  fungi tunic (duh), COF, RBG, RBB, Crescent Blades of Luclin, ect. </P><P>My personal take on trading is do not get too greedy on individual trades. Focus on going for more smaller trades rather then trying to make one big score. Try to keep your selling prices close to the generally accepted ceiling as you can. Trying to sell an RBG for 40K when the range on your sever is 30 to 35K will get you a bad rep pretty quick. Always be polite, even if the people you are dealing with are being pricks. And lastly, being a trader opens you up to more scammers, as the more trades you make, the more chances you have of running into a person who is trying to take you for a ride. Just use your head. Do not trade for items unless you are absolutetly sure of the other item's value and sellability. ALWAYS, and I cannot stress this enough ALWAYS right click on each item in the trade window before you hit trade. A popular little scam goes something like this:</P><P>Player 1 "WTB Fungi"<BR>Player 2 "I have one. How does 50K sound?"<BR>Player 1 starts to drool, as he/she knows fungis are worth way more on their server.<BR>Player 1 Puts 50K in the trade window. <BR>Player 2 puts a fungi in the trade window.<BR>Player 1 right clicks and confirms it is a fungi.<BR>Player 2 cancels the trade.<BR>Player 2 "Sorry. Lagging badly here. Try again."<BR>Player 1 puts 50K in the window.<BR>Player 2 puts an item with the same graphic as a fungi (say a cloth shirt) and hits trade quickly.<BR>Player 1 forgets to inspect the item a second time, and greed is clouding judgement. <BR>Player 1 hits trade and just bought a cloth tunic for 50K.</P><P>Just keep your head screwed on, and it is all good.</P><P>Cheers,<BR>Ancagalon the Black<BR>Warlock - Terris Thule</P><P> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
      </tr>

